<DocsLayout title=".primefile" description="The kernel identity document. Written by the OS, not by you. Records the running kernel version and signing authority.">
    <p>The kernel's identity document. The OS writes it. You read it to verify what's running.</p>

    <h2>What it is</h2>
    <p>
      The <code>.primefile</code> is the root of trust for the entire ostk installation.
      It is <strong>dual-signed</strong>: once by the kernel's own GPG key (T1), and once
      by the operator's personal GPG key (T0). Changes to the primefile require re-signing
      by both keys, in person.
    </p>
    <p>Read it to understand what kernel version is running, who signed it, and what the active trust chain looks like.</p>

    <h2>Location</h2>
    <p><code>.ostk/.primefile</code> &mdash; in your project's ostk state directory.</p>

    <h2>Example</h2>
    <pre><code>---BEGIN HAYSTACK.PRIME KERNEL DECLARATION---

KERNEL: @project.prime
VERSION: 2.0.0
CREATED: 2026-03-10T00:00:00Z
ROTATED: 2026-03-19T00:00:00Z

AUTHORITY:
  Primary: @operator (Human operator, HUMANFILE authority)
  Kernel: @project.prime (Persistent kernel, GOVERNANCE.md authority)
  Co-signers: Both keys required for mutation

KEYS:
  T0 Human Root:
    Name: Your Name &lt;you@example.com&gt;
    Key: AAAA...1111
    Algorithm: ed25519

  T1 Kernel:
    Name: @project.prime (v2.0) &lt;kernel@project.prime&gt;
    Key: BBBB...2222
    Algorithm: ed25519

  T1 CI:
    Name: @project.prime.ci &lt;ci@project.prime&gt;
    Key: CCCC...3333
    Algorithm: ed25519
    Cross-signed by: BBBB...2222

LINEAGE:
  Root: @operator GPG signature
  Co-sign: @project.prime GPG signature
  Chain: Unbroken from 2026-03-10

---SIGNATURES BELOW---</code></pre>

    <h2>Fields</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Field</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>KERNEL</code></td><td>Kernel identity name. Default: <code>@project.prime</code>.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>VERSION</code></td><td>Kernel declaration version.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>AUTHORITY</code></td><td>Who controls the kernel &mdash; primary (human), kernel, and co-signer requirements.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>KEYS</code></td><td>GPG key registry: T0 human root, T1 kernel, T1 CI. Algorithm and cross-signature info.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>LINEAGE</code></td><td>Root of trust chain, co-signers, and chain continuity date.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>Signature verification</h2>
    <pre><code>gpg --verify .ostk/.primefile.asc .ostk/.primefile</code></pre>
    <p>If verification fails, the kernel should not be trusted. The signature chain runs: human T0 key &rarr; kernel root key &rarr; CI key. Each link in the chain is cross-signed.</p>

    <h2>You don't edit this</h2>
    <p>
      Unlike HUMANFILE and ENTITYFILE, you do not write the primefile. The kernel owns it.
      Modifying it manually will invalidate the signature and may cause the kernel to
      refuse to boot.
    </p>

